The former prisoner, who is still believed to be locked-up in another prison, told police he had been an inmate of the prison when the bomb was buried underneath the floor. 

The cell had been used as a solitary confinement unit when the prison was functioning, but was later renovated into an art supply and storage room. 

Speaking to the ABC, The prison's executive manager Bevan Beaver said the bomb was not a danger to the public, even though visitors were taken past the cell where the bomb was buried.

